### Problem Description

When indexing documents using the bulk API, the `require_alias` flag can be used to ensure that all the indexing operations are being directed towards an alias instead of a concrete index. This allows a user to ensure their configuration is set up correctly and not accidentally create a new concrete index when they mean to use an alias. However, using the `POST /_bulk` API with the `?require_alias` flag (implicit 'true' value) does not work. Instead, the API requires explicitly specifying "true" as the value with `POST /_bulk?require_alias=true`. This is different than all of our other query string parameters, where the presence of the flag indicates an implicit true value (e.g., using `?pretty` as equivalent to `?pretty=true`).

### Steps to Reproduce

Compare the difference between:

```
POST _bulk?require_alias
{ "index" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "1" } }
{ "field1" : "value1" }
{ "delete" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "2" } }
{ "create" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "3" } }
{ "field1" : "value3" }
{ "update" : {"_id" : "1", "_index" : "test"} }
{ "doc" : {"field2" : "value2"} }
```

which allows all of the indexing operations to succeed (even though no aliases exist), and:

```
POST _bulk?require_alias=true
{ "index" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "1" } }
{ "field1" : "value1" }
{ "delete" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "2" } }
{ "create" : { "_index" : "test", "_id" : "3" } }
{ "field1" : "value3" }
{ "update" : {"_id" : "1", "_index" : "test"} }
{ "doc" : {"field2" : "value2"} }
```

Which blocks all the operations.

